\section{The state store}

The store separates two concerns:
\begin{description}
\item[Run records] JSON files under [[runs/]], one file per tutorial ID.
\item[Workspaces] persistent directories under [[workspaces/]], one
  directory per run.
\end{description}

This split keeps the bookkeeping files small while still giving each run
its own durable shell workspace.

<<classes>>=
class StateStore:
    """Store tutorial runs and workspaces on disk."""

    <<state store methods>>
@


\subsection{Initialising the store}

Embedded use matters here.  A standalone [[tutorial]] command should not
collide with a host application's built-in tutorials, so the store keeps
one namespace directory per host.

<<state store methods>>=
def __init__(
    self,
    root_dir: str | Path | None = None,
    *,
    namespace: str = "tutorial",
):
    """Initialise a state store for one host namespace."""

    if root_dir is None:
        base_dir = platformdirs.user_state_path(
            "tutorial",
            appauthor=False,
            ensure_exists=True,
        )
        self.root_dir = Path(base_dir) / namespace
    else:
        self.root_dir = Path(root_dir)

    self.namespace = namespace
    self.runs_dir = self.root_dir / "runs"
    self.workspaces_dir = self.root_dir / "workspaces"
    self.runs_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    self.workspaces_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_state_store_creates_runs_and_workspaces_dirs(tmp_path):
    store = StateStore(tmp_path)

    assert store.runs_dir.is_dir()
    assert store.workspaces_dir.is_dir()
@


\subsection{Locating the JSON file for one tutorial}

Each tutorial gets its own JSON file so that one broken record does not
block the rest of the registry.

<<state store methods>>=
def state_path(self, tutorial_id: str) -> Path:
    """Return the JSON file that stores runs for ``tutorial_id``."""

    return self.runs_dir / f"{tutorial_id}.json"
@

